<channel|>1. You would have to count to **one thousand**. (Numbers like "one hundred" or "nine hundred ninety-nine" do not contain the letter "a").

2. "The quick brown fox **jumps over the lazy dog.**" This sentence is famous for being a **pangram**, meaning it contains every letter of the English alphabet at least once.

3. Once upon a time, three little pigs were strolling through the woods, discussing the best way to build a house. As they argued, they spotted a young girl in a bright crimson cloak skipping toward them.

"Excuse me," the first pig said, "but are you lost?"

Little Red Riding Hood stopped and smiled. "Not at all! I'm bringing a basket of treats to my grandmother's house."

The pigs were intrigued, but the third pig, who was the most cautious, noticed a pair of hungry eyes watching them from the bushes. "Quickly!" he whispered. "The Big Bad Wolf is stalking us—and probably you, too!"

Red Riding Hood gasped, clutching her basket. "He tried to trick me earlier!"

The three pigs decided to team up. The first two pigs provided the distraction, dancing and singing loudly to lure the wolf into the open, while the third pig and Red Riding Hood worked together to set a clever trap. They used a sturdy rope and a heavy basket of stones to create a tripwire across the path.

When the wolf lunged forward, hoping for a feast of pork and pastry, he tripped spectacularly, tumbling head-over-heels into a muddy ditch. 

With the wolf stuck and grumbling, the pigs escorted Red Riding Hood safely to her grandmother's cottage. In gratitude, she shared her treats with them, and the three pigs decided that while bricks were great for houses, friendship was the best protection of all. [end of text]


